WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.495 align:middle line:90%
[WIND RUSTLING]

00:00:02.495 --> 00:06:27.680 align:middle line:90%


00:06:27.680 --> 00:06:31.640 align:middle line:10%
>> I was lucky to live in a
house when I was growing up

00:06:31.640 --> 00:06:37.025 align:middle line:10%
as a child that was located
in quite a silent location.

00:06:37.025 --> 00:06:40.090 align:middle line:90%


00:06:40.090 --> 00:06:42.250 align:middle line:84%
There was also a good view
out my bedroom window.

00:06:42.250 --> 00:06:44.770 align:middle line:90%


00:06:44.770 --> 00:06:50.300 align:middle line:10%
And I guess, as a young
child, I fell in love with it.

00:06:50.300 --> 00:06:52.810 align:middle line:84%
But I didn't know what
that meant at all.

00:06:52.810 --> 00:06:54.820 align:middle line:84%
I didn't even know what
it was, to be honest.

00:06:54.820 --> 00:07:14.990 align:middle line:90%


00:07:14.990 --> 00:07:19.490 align:middle line:84%
So how do you talk
coherently about silence?

00:07:19.490 --> 00:07:21.510 align:middle line:84%
We could talk about
silence, does it

00:07:21.510 --> 00:07:25.130 align:middle line:90%
exist in a decibel sense?

00:07:25.130 --> 00:07:28.150 align:middle line:84%
A noise sense or a
lack of noise sense?

00:07:28.150 --> 00:07:29.880 align:middle line:84%
And the literature's
clear that silence

00:07:29.880 --> 00:07:31.080 align:middle line:90%
doesn't exist in that sense.

00:07:31.080 --> 00:07:50.270 align:middle line:90%


00:07:50.270 --> 00:07:53.210 align:middle line:84%
>> The etymological roots of the
word for silence are somewhat

00:07:53.210 --> 00:07:54.440 align:middle line:90%
contested.

00:07:54.440 --> 00:07:56.180 align:middle line:84%
There are two words,
in particular,

00:07:56.180 --> 00:07:57.240 align:middle line:90%
that people go back to.

00:07:57.240 --> 00:08:02.630 align:middle line:84%
There's a Gothic term,
anasidan and then desinary.

00:08:02.630 --> 00:08:05.540 align:middle line:84%
One of them has to do
with the wind dying down

00:08:05.540 --> 00:08:10.170 align:middle line:84%
and the other has to do with
a kind of stopping of motion.

00:08:10.170 --> 00:08:12.420 align:middle line:84%
They're both to do
with an interruption,

00:08:12.420 --> 00:08:15.720 align:middle line:84%
not just of sound, but
the roots of sounds

00:08:15.720 --> 00:08:19.110 align:middle line:84%
are also due to do with the
interruption of the imposition

00:08:19.110 --> 00:08:20.580 align:middle line:90%
of our own egos on the world.

00:08:20.580 --> 00:09:08.560 align:middle line:90%


00:09:08.560 --> 00:09:11.860 align:middle line:84%
>> Almost all of the early
theologians talk about,

00:09:11.860 --> 00:09:15.400 align:middle line:84%
the ultimate wish of God is
silence and that God dwells

00:09:15.400 --> 00:09:16.870 align:middle line:90%
in the silence of eternity.

00:09:16.870 --> 00:09:20.216 align:middle line:90%


00:09:20.216 --> 00:09:22.606 align:middle line:90%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:09:22.606 --> 00:09:26.430 align:middle line:90%


00:09:26.430 --> 00:09:29.060 align:middle line:84%
The history of monastic life
is as old as the history

00:09:29.060 --> 00:09:32.150 align:middle line:90%
of the human race.

00:09:32.150 --> 00:09:34.340 align:middle line:10%
I think, the whole
history of shamans

00:09:34.340 --> 00:09:37.400 align:middle line:10%
is a history of a kind
of proto-monasticism,

00:09:37.400 --> 00:09:41.000 align:middle line:10%
where someone in the tribe
has clearly evidently,

00:09:41.000 --> 00:09:43.550 align:middle line:10%
a facility with
silence and a facility

00:09:43.550 --> 00:09:47.930 align:middle line:10%
with understanding the unspoken
processes of the world.

00:09:47.930 --> 00:11:52.323 align:middle line:90%


00:11:52.323 --> 00:11:54.808 align:middle line:90%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:11:54.808 --> 00:12:26.892 align:middle line:90%


00:12:26.892 --> 00:12:29.900 align:middle line:84%
>> Retreating from the cacophony
of the world is stepping

00:12:29.900 --> 00:12:32.651 align:middle line:84%
towards everything
that's essential.

00:12:32.651 --> 00:12:36.980 align:middle line:90%


00:12:36.980 --> 00:12:39.230 align:middle line:84%
It's about stepping towards
the world and really,

00:12:39.230 --> 00:12:41.150 align:middle line:84%
about learning how to
love the world, again.

00:12:41.150 --> 00:12:48.090 align:middle line:90%


00:12:48.090 --> 00:12:51.480 align:middle line:84%
>> Historically, solitude has
always had an exalted place

00:12:51.480 --> 00:12:54.390 align:middle line:84%
in our culture and it's really,
only recently that it has

00:12:54.390 --> 00:12:59.070 align:middle line:84%
fallen grace and now needs to be
restored to its rightful place.

00:12:59.070 --> 00:13:01.200 align:middle line:84%
You look at all the
religious traditions--

00:13:01.200 --> 00:13:04.760 align:middle line:84%
Buddha, Jesus, and
Mohammad, and Moses-- these

00:13:04.760 --> 00:13:07.620 align:middle line:84%
were all seekers who would
go off into the woods,

00:13:07.620 --> 00:13:11.700 align:middle line:84%
think their thoughts, have their
revelations, and then come back

00:13:11.700 --> 00:13:14.040 align:middle line:84%
and share those revelations
with the wider world.

00:13:14.040 --> 00:13:18.610 align:middle line:90%


00:13:18.610 --> 00:13:21.020 align:middle line:84%
We lose a lot when we
don't allow people--

00:13:21.020 --> 00:13:23.510 align:middle line:84%
and not just allow,
but encourage people

00:13:23.510 --> 00:13:26.120 align:middle line:90%
to go off by themselves.

00:13:26.120 --> 00:13:28.580 align:middle line:84%
Whether literally into the
woods or metaphorically,

00:13:28.580 --> 00:13:32.410 align:middle line:84%
to just go and chart your own
journey and do it by yourself.

00:13:32.410 --> 00:13:34.340 align:middle line:84%
And there are certain
paths in this life

00:13:34.340 --> 00:13:36.730 align:middle line:84%
that you've got to
walk alone and that's

00:13:36.730 --> 00:13:37.730 align:middle line:90%
the only way to do them.

00:13:37.730 --> 00:14:32.897 align:middle line:90%


00:14:32.897 --> 00:14:35.382 align:middle line:90%
[GONGS]

00:14:35.382 --> 00:15:27.200 align:middle line:90%


00:15:27.200 --> 00:16:35.354 align:middle line:10%
>> [NON-ENGLISH SPEECH]

00:16:35.354 --> 00:16:37.512 align:middle line:90%
[BELLS RINGING]

00:16:37.512 --> 00:16:38.312 align:middle line:90%


00:16:38.312 --> 00:16:40.284 align:middle line:90%
[CHANTING IN NON-ENGLISH SPEECH]

00:16:40.284 --> 00:17:25.406 align:middle line:90%


00:17:25.406 --> 00:17:27.560 align:middle line:84%
>> Will you tell
our panel, please,

00:17:27.560 --> 00:17:29.920 align:middle line:84%
what your name is and
where you're from.

00:17:29.920 --> 00:17:31.660 align:middle line:90%
>> My name is John Cage.

00:17:31.660 --> 00:17:33.820 align:middle line:90%
I'm from Stony Point, New York.

00:17:33.820 --> 00:17:36.220 align:middle line:84%
>> He is probably, the
most controversial figure

00:17:36.220 --> 00:17:39.200 align:middle line:84%
in the musical world today and
when you hear his performance--

00:17:39.200 --> 00:17:42.090 align:middle line:84%
if you will forgive me--
you will understand why.

00:17:42.090 --> 00:17:45.210 align:middle line:84%
The instruments that he will
use include a water pitcher,

00:17:45.210 --> 00:17:49.990 align:middle line:84%
an iron pipe, a goose call, a
bathtub, five radios all hooked

00:17:49.990 --> 00:17:51.440 align:middle line:90%
up, and a grand piano.

00:17:51.440 --> 00:17:52.240 align:middle line:90%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:17:52.240 --> 00:17:57.490 align:middle line:10%
>> Between 1950 and 1952, when
Cage created his most important

00:17:57.490 --> 00:18:02.334 align:middle line:10%
piece of music, Cage had
a series of revelations

00:18:02.334 --> 00:18:04.750 align:middle line:10%
and the revelations informed
the rest of his life and they

00:18:04.750 --> 00:18:06.250 align:middle line:10%
informed the rest
of his music, too.

00:18:06.250 --> 00:18:09.540 align:middle line:90%


00:18:09.540 --> 00:18:12.960 align:middle line:84%
He'd been interested in
silence for a long time

00:18:12.960 --> 00:18:17.030 align:middle line:84%
and he had been appreciating
noise for a long time.

00:18:17.030 --> 00:18:21.040 align:middle line:90%


00:18:21.040 --> 00:18:24.732 align:middle line:84%
So he had this dualism
about science versus noise

00:18:24.732 --> 00:18:28.510 align:middle line:84%
so he was looking for silence
as an alternative to noise.

00:18:28.510 --> 00:18:34.380 align:middle line:90%


00:18:34.380 --> 00:18:40.120 align:middle line:84%
When he ventured into an
antecourt chamber in Boston,

00:18:40.120 --> 00:18:42.060 align:middle line:84%
he was looking for the
quietest place on Earth

00:18:42.060 --> 00:18:45.210 align:middle line:84%
because Ramakrishna had
said, find the silence

00:18:45.210 --> 00:18:46.140 align:middle line:90%
and you will find God.

00:18:46.140 --> 00:19:04.450 align:middle line:90%


00:19:04.450 --> 00:19:08.720 align:middle line:84%
>> And I heard in
that room, two songs.

00:19:08.720 --> 00:19:11.910 align:middle line:90%
One was high and one was low.

00:19:11.910 --> 00:19:15.220 align:middle line:84%
And I thought, there was
something wrong with the room.

00:19:15.220 --> 00:19:20.010 align:middle line:84%
I went outside and I found the
engineer in charge and he said,

00:19:20.010 --> 00:19:24.410 align:middle line:84%
the high one was your
nervous system in operation.

00:19:24.410 --> 00:19:27.338 align:middle line:84%
And the low one was
your blood circulating.

00:19:27.338 --> 00:19:34.040 align:middle line:90%


00:19:34.040 --> 00:19:39.900 align:middle line:84%
>> He realizes that
silence is an abstraction.

00:19:39.900 --> 00:19:42.060 align:middle line:90%
It's a human concept.

00:19:42.060 --> 00:19:45.830 align:middle line:84%
And what's actually happening
is that Cage and his own body

00:19:45.830 --> 00:19:50.330 align:middle line:84%
and his own being is completely
interconnected with all beings

00:19:50.330 --> 00:19:52.850 align:middle line:84%
and all bodies of
beings everywhere,

00:19:52.850 --> 00:19:56.140 align:middle line:84%
and that everyone
shares the same ground.

00:19:56.140 --> 00:20:06.490 align:middle line:84%
>> Then it became clear, that
the function of art is not

00:20:06.490 --> 00:20:11.410 align:middle line:84%
to communicate one's personal
ideas or feelings, but rather,

00:20:11.410 --> 00:20:16.850 align:middle line:84%
to imitate nature in
her manner of operation.

00:20:16.850 --> 00:20:34.330 align:middle line:90%


00:20:34.330 --> 00:20:37.930 align:middle line:84%
>> Cage's most important
piece of music is--

00:20:37.930 --> 00:20:41.180 align:middle line:84%
as many people know--
actually not music at all.

00:20:41.180 --> 00:20:43.690 align:middle line:84%
It's four and a half
minutes of silence.

00:20:43.690 --> 00:20:56.990 align:middle line:90%


00:20:56.990 --> 00:21:00.930 align:middle line:84%
When Cage first performed
that piece with David Tudor--

00:21:00.930 --> 00:21:04.320 align:middle line:84%
his pianist-- he performed
it in Woodstock, New York,

00:21:04.320 --> 00:21:08.340 align:middle line:84%
at a little bar called
Maverick Concert House.

00:21:08.340 --> 00:21:11.670 align:middle line:90%
And the audience went berserk.

00:21:11.670 --> 00:21:12.960 align:middle line:90%
This was 1952--

00:21:12.960 --> 00:21:15.550 align:middle line:90%
August 29th, 1952.

00:21:15.550 --> 00:21:16.790 align:middle line:90%
>> They were incensed.

00:21:16.790 --> 00:21:19.880 align:middle line:84%
They were in an uproar
over the performance.

00:21:19.880 --> 00:21:26.130 align:middle line:10%
And afterwards, John opened
the floor to questions and one

00:21:26.130 --> 00:21:29.140 align:middle line:10%
of the artists got up and
said, good people of Woodstock,

00:21:29.140 --> 00:21:32.879 align:middle line:10%
I think we should run
these people out of town.

00:21:32.879 --> 00:21:33.795 align:middle line:90%
That was the reaction.

00:21:33.795 --> 00:22:10.976 align:middle line:90%


00:22:10.976 --> 00:22:13.471 align:middle line:90%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:22:13.471 --> 00:23:10.440 align:middle line:90%


00:23:10.440 --> 00:23:15.180 align:middle line:84%
>> Silence is where we
hear something deeper than

00:23:15.180 --> 00:23:16.620 align:middle line:90%
our chatter.

00:23:16.620 --> 00:23:19.454 align:middle line:84%
And silence is where
we speak something

00:23:19.454 --> 00:23:20.370 align:middle line:90%
deeper than our words.

00:23:20.370 --> 00:23:41.710 align:middle line:90%


00:23:41.710 --> 00:23:44.650 align:middle line:84%
All of us know that the most
essential things in life

00:23:44.650 --> 00:23:46.160 align:middle line:84%
are exactly what
we can't express.

00:23:46.160 --> 00:23:48.806 align:middle line:90%


00:23:48.806 --> 00:23:50.150 align:middle line:90%
Our relation to faith.

00:23:50.150 --> 00:23:52.010 align:middle line:90%
Our relation to love.

00:23:52.010 --> 00:23:53.255 align:middle line:90%
Our relation to death.

00:23:53.255 --> 00:23:57.900 align:middle line:90%
Our relation to divinity.

00:23:57.900 --> 00:24:00.270 align:middle line:84%
So I think, silence
is the resting place

00:24:00.270 --> 00:24:02.037 align:middle line:90%
of everything essential.

00:24:02.037 --> 00:24:07.290 align:middle line:90%


00:24:07.290 --> 00:24:11.760 align:middle line:84%
>> For the first, I don't know
how many hundred thousand years

00:24:11.760 --> 00:24:15.470 align:middle line:84%
of human life, when we were on
the Savannah or running about

00:24:15.470 --> 00:24:18.540 align:middle line:84%
the forest, silence was
essential to our survival.

00:24:18.540 --> 00:24:23.360 align:middle line:90%


00:24:23.360 --> 00:24:26.710 align:middle line:84%
So silence is our natural
milieu, and the farther

00:24:26.710 --> 00:24:29.802 align:middle line:84%
we get away from silence, the
more we lose our humanity.

00:24:29.802 --> 00:24:39.442 align:middle line:90%


00:24:39.442 --> 00:24:41.870 align:middle line:90%
[INTERPOSING VOICES]

00:24:41.870 --> 00:24:55.550 align:middle line:90%


00:24:55.550 --> 00:24:58.190 align:middle line:10%
>> American individualism
now, has become more and more

00:24:58.190 --> 00:25:03.050 align:middle line:10%
associated with our
right and our, almost,

00:25:03.050 --> 00:25:05.600 align:middle line:10%
social obligation to impose
our will on the world.

00:25:05.600 --> 00:25:07.130 align:middle line:10%
To get out our thoughts.

00:25:07.130 --> 00:25:08.030 align:middle line:10%
To not hesitate.

00:25:08.030 --> 00:25:09.990 align:middle line:10%
To not be shy.

00:25:09.990 --> 00:25:22.060 align:middle line:10%
[INTERPOSING VOICES]

00:25:22.060 --> 00:25:26.390 align:middle line:10%
>> There is such an
intense, overwhelming drive

00:25:26.390 --> 00:25:29.420 align:middle line:10%
to contribute our little
ricocheting response to this

00:25:29.420 --> 00:25:31.380 align:middle line:10%
soul-crushing din of the moment.

00:25:31.380 --> 00:25:32.720 align:middle line:90%
[INTERPOSING VOICES]

00:25:32.720 --> 00:26:15.730 align:middle line:90%


00:26:15.730 --> 00:26:19.150 align:middle line:84%
>> Throughout Japanese history,
there has been an appreciation

00:26:19.150 --> 00:26:21.300 align:middle line:84%
of softer, quieter
registers of being.

00:26:21.300 --> 00:26:27.656 align:middle line:90%


00:26:27.656 --> 00:26:30.220 align:middle line:84%
One of the most signal
instances of this

00:26:30.220 --> 00:26:32.920 align:middle line:84%
is really, in relationship
to the tea ceremony.

00:26:32.920 --> 00:26:50.240 align:middle line:90%


00:26:50.240 --> 00:26:53.450 align:middle line:84%
One of the most important
masters, Sen Rikyu,

00:26:53.450 --> 00:27:00.020 align:middle line:84%
lived at a time of
incredible martial activity

00:27:00.020 --> 00:27:03.620 align:middle line:90%
among different samurai groups.

00:27:03.620 --> 00:27:09.290 align:middle line:84%
And part of his interest in
developing the tea ceremony

00:27:09.290 --> 00:27:11.510 align:middle line:84%
in the ways that he
did, was to cultivate

00:27:11.510 --> 00:27:15.740 align:middle line:84%
an appreciation for silence
and silence's relationship

00:27:15.740 --> 00:27:18.370 align:middle line:84%
to a more specific
environment, in general.

00:27:18.370 --> 00:27:24.460 align:middle line:90%


00:27:24.460 --> 00:28:03.066 align:middle line:10%
>> [NON-ENGLISH SPEECH]

00:28:03.066 --> 00:28:05.556 align:middle line:90%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:28:05.556 --> 00:28:09.090 align:middle line:90%


00:28:09.090 --> 00:28:38.900 align:middle line:10%
>> [NON-ENGLISH SPEECH]

00:28:38.900 --> 00:28:40.150 align:middle line:10%
[NON-ENGLISH SPEECH]

00:28:40.150 --> 00:29:01.780 align:middle line:90%


00:29:01.780 --> 00:29:05.770 align:middle line:84%
>> Silence allows everybody to
have equal platform and equal

00:29:05.770 --> 00:29:09.590 align:middle line:84%
voice because if nobody's
talking, nobody's dominating.

00:29:09.590 --> 00:29:56.680 align:middle line:90%


00:29:56.680 --> 00:29:59.530 align:middle line:84%
>> Silence is a
sound, and I think,

00:29:59.530 --> 00:30:00.990 align:middle line:84%
it's a sound with
many qualities.

00:30:00.990 --> 00:30:10.159 align:middle line:90%


00:30:10.159 --> 00:30:11.700 align:middle line:84%
And I think, if we
start to cultivate

00:30:11.700 --> 00:30:14.550 align:middle line:84%
an appreciation of silence
as the precious thing it

00:30:14.550 --> 00:30:18.150 align:middle line:84%
is and enjoy it for
a few minutes a day,

00:30:18.150 --> 00:30:21.210 align:middle line:84%
then it gives us a proper
relationship with sound,

00:30:21.210 --> 00:30:24.330 align:middle line:90%
with noise, with our own sound.

00:30:24.330 --> 00:30:26.459 align:middle line:10%
It allows us to be much
more balanced in the way

00:30:26.459 --> 00:30:28.500 align:middle line:10%
that we relate to the
world, much more conscious.

00:30:28.500 --> 00:30:33.140 align:middle line:90%


00:30:33.140 --> 00:30:38.810 align:middle line:84%
>> When we throw around the
term of silence, we may,

00:30:38.810 --> 00:30:41.330 align:middle line:84%
in the first instance, imagine
that we're seeking some kind

00:30:41.330 --> 00:30:44.540 align:middle line:84%
of absolute quiet, but very,
very few people look for that.

00:30:44.540 --> 00:30:45.730 align:middle line:90%
What we're looking--

00:30:45.730 --> 00:30:48.020 align:middle line:84%
I came to believe--
is really, more

00:30:48.020 --> 00:30:51.190 align:middle line:84%
for a balance in
our environment.

00:30:51.190 --> 00:30:55.210 align:middle line:84%
It's the particular
balance of sound and quiet

00:30:55.210 --> 00:31:00.340 align:middle line:84%
that maximizes our perceptual
awareness of where we are.

00:31:00.340 --> 00:31:27.350 align:middle line:90%


00:31:27.350 --> 00:31:29.150 align:middle line:10%
[MAKING ANIMAL SOUNDS]

00:31:29.150 --> 00:31:30.610 align:middle line:90%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:31:30.610 --> 00:31:46.030 align:middle line:90%


00:31:46.030 --> 00:31:49.825 align:middle line:84%
>> Sounds a little bit like
one of those toys you see,

00:31:49.825 --> 00:31:50.680 align:middle line:90%
you shake it.

00:31:50.680 --> 00:31:53.600 align:middle line:84%
It's like a little
[MAKING NOISES]

00:31:53.600 --> 00:31:55.950 align:middle line:90%
that sort of a [MAKING NOISES].

00:31:55.950 --> 00:32:07.085 align:middle line:90%


00:32:07.085 --> 00:32:09.069 align:middle line:84%
Probably should leave
them be, I suppose.

00:32:09.069 --> 00:32:14.700 align:middle line:90%


00:32:14.700 --> 00:32:19.650 align:middle line:84%
The first superintendent of
this park, Harry Karstens,

00:32:19.650 --> 00:32:24.090 align:middle line:84%
he was very aware of the
solitude and quietude

00:32:24.090 --> 00:32:25.680 align:middle line:90%
of this place.

00:32:25.680 --> 00:32:29.250 align:middle line:84%
And he had an interesting
quote in 1924,

00:32:29.250 --> 00:32:33.180 align:middle line:84%
when he said, "there
is much to learn

00:32:33.180 --> 00:32:35.340 align:middle line:84%
by those who
understand the language

00:32:35.340 --> 00:32:36.690 align:middle line:90%
of the great silent places."

